‘Beloved by the Muses l can throw to the winds all fears of dangers frorn abroad. Sweet Muse, weave a chaplet for my Lamia,l pray. My verse is naught without thee. Celebrate him in Lesbian song)

The Lamia here addressed has been identified with L. Aelius Lamia, one of the two sons of Cicero's friend and supportes, L. Aelius Lamia who was praetor 43 nc. (Cic. adsum. 11, 16, ²3 pro Sest. 29). Lamia must have been young at the time this ode was written, for he was consul in 3 An). and praefectus urbi in 32 Aa). He died the following year. Tacitus, Ana. 6, 27, mentions him, gemes illi decorum vivida senectam· Velleius Paterculus describes him (2, 116, 3), vir an- tiqm'ssimi neoris, et priscam gravitatem semper hiernanitate temperans.
